The role of cytology in the diagnosis and follow-up of patients with cervical adenocarcinoma. A review was undertaken of the 121 patients with cervical adenocarcinoma, ranging in age from 10 to 91 years, who had cytology specimens examined in this laboratory. All but two had cervicovaginal smears. Fifty-eight patients had cervical smears taken prior to treatment 91% of these contained malignant cells. The commonest histologic subtype was mucinous adenocarcinoma (61 patients